### Description

Currently, the callback functions in `provideSignalFormsConfig‚Äôs` classes config receive only the signal state:

```ts
provideSignalFormsConfig({
  classes: {
    'border-red-500': (s) => s.invalid(),
    'border-green-500': (s) => s.valid(),
  },
})
```

**Problem:**
Sometimes the class condition needs to depend not only on the signal state, but also on the native HTML element itself (e.g., its attributes, dataset, or current computed style). Right now, there‚Äôs no way to access the element in these callbacks.

**Feature request:**
Pass the underlying HTML element as a second argument to the callback, e.g.:

```ts
provideSignalFormsConfig({
  classes: {
    'border-red-500': (s, el) => s.invalid() && el.type === 'INPUT',
  },
})
```

This would make conditional styling more flexible and allow decisions based on both signal state and element properties.

### Proposed solution

```ts
provideSignalFormsConfig({
  classes: {
    'border-red-500': (s, el) => s.invalid() && el.type === 'INPUT',
  },
})
```

